{
  "doc_id": "8420",
  "text": "S. mansoni has just two PLK genes, Smplk1 and Smsak (Smplk4) (GenBank IDs AAV49163 and GU084154, respectively), which is in contrast to the five found in humans [CITATION_1] [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] . PLKs are a family of conserved serine/threonine kinases, which, in humans, are involved in cell division, including G2/M transition, centrosome maturation, formation of bipolar spindles, cytokinesis and regulation of the spindle assembly checkpoint [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] [CITATION_6] [CITATION_7] . Plk1 is the best characterized member of the family and is vital to normal mitotic progression [CITATION_8] [CITATION_9] [CITATION_10] [CITATION_11] [CITATION_12] . Its overexpression in human tumors [CITATION_13] [CITATION_14] [CITATION_15] has identified this kinase as a selective target for anti-cancer drugs.",
